# âœï¸ Linux File Editing with vi & vim

## ğŸ–‹ï¸ What is a File Editor?
- A **file editor** allows creating and editing text files.
- Common Linux editors: `vi`, `ed`, `ex`, `emacs`, `pico`, and `vim`.
- **vi** is available on almost every Linux distribution.
- **vim** is an enhanced version of `vi` with more features.

---

## âš™ï¸ vi Editor Basics

### **Start Editing**
```bash
vi filename
Opens the file (creates if it doesn't exist).

Two modes:

Command mode â€“ Navigate, delete, copy, save.

Insert mode â€“ Type text (i to enter insert mode).

Insert & Save
Press i â†’ Insert Mode (bottom shows -- INSERT --).

Type your content.

Press Esc â†’ return to Command Mode.

Save & Exit:

:wq or :x â†’ Save & quit.

Shift + ZZ â†’ Save & quit (shortcut).

:q! â†’ Quit without saving.

Navigation Keys
Use Arrow Keys or h (left), j (down), k (up), l (right).

0 â†’ Move to line start.

$ â†’ Move to line end.

G â†’ Go to end of file.

gg â†’ Go to start of file.

Editing Text
x â†’ Delete a single character.

dd â†’ Delete current line.

u â†’ Undo last change.

r + <char> â†’ Replace character under cursor.

o â†’ Create a new line below and enter insert mode.

O â†’ Create a new line above and enter insert mode.

Search in vi
/word â†’ Search forward.

?word â†’ Search backward.

n â†’ Repeat search forward.

N â†’ Repeat search backward.

vim Editor
vim = vi Improved â€“ includes:

Syntax highlighting

Spell check

Autocomplete (Tab completion)

Undo history

Plugins & scripting

Comparison (vimdiff)

GUI support

ğŸ§  Key Differences: vi vs vim
Feature	vi	vim
Availability	Everywhere	May need installation
Syntax Highlight	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Undo/Redo	Limited	Multiple levels
